  "prompt_text": "What is the pigeonhole principle? Give three non-trivial applications.",
  "response_text": "The pigeonhole principle states that if there are more pigeons than pigeonholes and each pigeon must be housed in one of the pigeonholes, then at least one pigeonhole must contain more than one pigeon.\n\nThree non-trivial applications of the pigeonhole principle include:\n\n1. **Divide and Conquer Strategy**: In computer science, the pigeonhole principle can be used to divide a problem into smaller subproblems. For example, when sorting an array of n elements, it's often easier to sort the first k elements than the rest because the pigeonhole principle guarantees that at least one of these k elements will be sorted before all the remaining elements.\n\n2. **Optimization Techniques**: The principle has been applied in various optimization problems. For instance, in scheduling algorithms, the principle helps in determining the optimal order for processing tasks to minimize total completion time or maximize resource utilization.\n\n3. **Data Analysis**: In data analysis, the principle is used to identify patterns or outliers in large datasets. By grouping similar observations together based on certain criteria, we can make more informed decisions about the dataset.\n\nThese applications demonstrate how the pigeonhole principle is fundamental in solving complex problems efficiently.",
